# Game Metadata Enrichment (IGDB)

We do not store rich game metadata (description, screenshots, developer, etc.) in
Postgres. We persist *deal* data plus compact **`genres`** and **`rating`** snapshots
on each deal (`020-data-model.mdc`). IGDB fills those **only as ingestion fallbacks**
when the store didn't; other catalog fields stay render-time enrichment.

## Why IGDB over RAWG

IGDB's `external_games` endpoint maps Steam App IDs directly to IGDB game
records — exact matching against `NormalizedDeal.steamAppId`, no fuzzy title
search. RAWG doesn't offer this, and fuzzy title matching across storefronts is
a real source of bugs (wrong edition, wrong game entirely) we'd rather not have.

## Auth

- IGDB sits behind Twitch's OAuth2 client-credentials flow, not a simple API key.
  Exchange `IGDB_CLIENT_ID` / `IGDB_CLIENT_SECRET` for a bearer token via
  `https://id.twitch.tv/oauth2/token`, cache the token server-side for its
  `expires_in` duration (it's long-lived — no need to refresh per-request), and
  send `Client-ID` + `Authorization: Bearer <token>` on every IGDB call.
- Token caching lives in `lib/enrichment/igdb-auth.ts`. Don't fetch a fresh
  token per request — that's wasteful and unnecessary given the long expiry.
- IGDB is rate-limited to ~4 requests/second — batch lookups where possible using
  IGDB's multiquery support rather than firing requests in a loop.

## Genres & rating — ingestion fallback, not listing default

- **Source normalizers own genres and rating when the store exposes them** — IGDB
  is second choice, never first.
- During cron, after `fetchDeals()` + normalize: for deals still missing `genres`
  and/or `rating` with a `steamAppId`, batch IGDB lookups and merge onto deals
  before upsert. One shared helper e.g. `enrichDealsFromIgdb(deals: NormalizedDeal[])`
  in `lib/enrichment/` — **one batch per unique `steamAppId`**, copy both genres
  and rating from the same `GameMetadata` response. Callable from cron routes only.
- If source already set `genres` and/or `rating`, skip IGDB for that field — do
  not overwrite source values.
- Exact `steamAppId` match only — no fuzzy title search for backfill.
- `GameMetadata` and `NormalizedDeal` stay separate types; copy values at ingestion.

## Fetch pattern (render-time catalog fields)

- `lib/enrichment/igdb.ts` exports something like
  `getGameMetadata(steamAppId: string): Promise<GameMetadata | null>`.
- IGDB uses POST + the Apicalypse query syntax, not query-string REST — don't
  write GET requests against it.
- Wrap IGDB calls in Next 16's `'use cache'` with per-game tags and
  `cacheLife('days')`. See `080-caching.mdc` for batching and negative caching.
- Listing pages batch unique `steamAppId`s via `getGameMetadataForSteamAppIds()`
  for **cover/description only** when needed — not for genres/rating if already on
  the deal row from Postgres.
- If IGDB has no match for a `steamAppId` (or the deal has none, e.g. most
  console-store items), degrade gracefully — render the deal using only
  `NormalizedDeal` fields, don't block the page or throw.

## Shape

```typescript
interface GameMetadata {
  igdbId: number;
  description: string | null;
  genres: string[];
  coverUrl: string | null;
  screenshotUrls: string[];
  rating: number | null;       // IGDB aggregated rating
  releaseDate: string | null;  // ISO date
}
```

This type lives in `types/enrichment.ts`, separate from `NormalizedDeal` —
never merge the two into one shape, even at the component prop level. Keeping
them distinct is what keeps the "no game data in Postgres" boundary enforceable.
